3. System Architecture & Components

3.1 Transmitter Subsystem

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                 TRANSMITTER SYSTEM                  │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Power Supply → DC-AC Converter → Beamformer → Array│
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

3.1.1 Piezoelectric Transducer Array

· Material Selection Matrix:

Material d₃₃ (pC/N) kₜ Acoustic Impedance (MRayl) Application
PZT-5H 593 0.50 30 General purpose
PMN-PT 1500-2000 0.55-0.60 20-25 High performance
AlN (MEMS) 5.5 0.25 34 Integrated systems
PVDF 20-30 0.10-0.15 4 Flexible arrays

· Array Geometry: Hexagonal close packing optimizes fill factor (>90%) while minimizing grating lobes.

3.1.2 Driving Electronics

· Amplifier Topology: Class-D switching amplifiers achieve >85% electrical efficiency
· Voltage Requirements: 100-400 Vpp depending on transducer capacitance and desired output
· Frequency Stability: <100 ppm to maintain resonance tracking

3.1.3 Beamforming Processor

· Architecture: FPGA + DSP hybrid for real-time processing
· Algorithm: Time-reversal focusing with phase conjugation
· Resolution: 12-bit phase control (0.088° at 250 kHz)

3.2 Receiver Subsystem

3.2.1 Acoustic Reception

· Piezoelectric Conversion: Identical principle to transmitter, operating in receive mode
· Array Configuration: Sparse arrays reduce cost while maintaining directional sensitivity
· Matching Network: Tunable LC network compensates for detuning due to environmental changes

3.2.2 Power Conversion Chain

```
Acoustic → Electrical → Rectification → Regulation → Load
   ↓          ↓           ↓           ↓         ↓
  MEMS      Matching   Active-Diode  Buck-Boost 3.3/5/12V
 Receiver    Network      Bridge    Converter    Output
```

3.2.3 Maximum Power Point Tracking (MPPT)

· Algorithm: Perturb and Observe (P&O) with adaptive step size
· Tracking Efficiency: >99% under varying acoustic intensity
· Response Time: <100 ms for 90% step change

3.3 Control & Feedback System

3.3.1 Backscatter Communication

· Modulation: Load modulation at 2.4 GHz ISM band
· Data Rate: 100 kbps sufficient for power telemetry
· Protocol: Time-division multiplexing for multi-receiver systems

3.3.2 Alignment & Tracking

· Coarse Alignment: IR beacon with ±5° accuracy
· Fine Alignment: Phase correlation of received signals across array
· Tracking Bandwidth: 10 Hz sufficient for human motion

---

4. Performance Characteristics & Limitations

4.1 Efficiency Analysis

System Efficiency Decomposition:

\eta_{system} = \eta_{elec-ac} \times \eta_{prop} \times \eta_{ac-elec} \times \eta_{conv}

Where:

· \eta_{elec-ac} = Electrical to acoustic conversion (75-85%)
· \eta_{prop} = Propagation efficiency (distance and medium dependent)
· \eta_{ac-elec} = Acoustic to electrical conversion (70-80%)
· \eta_{conv} = Power conversion efficiency (85-95%)

Propagation Loss Model:
For a directional transmitter with gain G_t illuminating a receiver of area A_r at distance d:

P_r = P_t \frac{G_t A_r}{4\pi d^2} e^{-2\alpha d}

The effective transmission gain is:

G_{eff} = \frac{A_t A_r}{\lambda^2 d^2} e^{-2\alpha d}

Where A_t is the transmitter aperture area.

4.2 Frequency Selection Trade-offs

Frequency Wavelength in Air Attenuation at 1m Beam Divergence Typical Application
40 kHz 8.6 mm 2.6% 15° (D=10λ) Consumer devices
250 kHz 1.4 mm 10% 5° (D=10λ) Medical systems
1 MHz 0.34 mm 32% 2° (D=10λ) High-precision industrial

4.3 Practical Performance Boundaries

Current State-of-the-Art:

· Efficiency: 60% DC-to-DC at 30 cm, dropping to 15% at 3 m
· Power Density: 1 W/cm² achievable at receiver, safety-limited
· Beam Steering: ±60° electronic steering without mechanical movement
· Multi-beam: 4 simultaneous beams with 20 dB isolation

Theoretical Limits:

· Maximum Efficiency: 85% constrained by material losses and impedance matching
· Maximum Range: 10 m in air at 40 kHz (limited by attenuation and beam spreading)
· Maximum Power: 100 W continuous per array (thermal limited)

---

5. Advanced Beamforming & Control Systems

5.1 Adaptive Beamforming Algorithms

5.1.1 Time-Reversal Focusing
The time-reversal operator T applied to received signals s_i(t) from initial transmission:

T[s_i(t)] = s_i(-t)

When retransmitted, this creates constructive interference at the receiver location. The focusing gain is:

G_{TR} = \frac{N^2}{\sum_{i=1}^N \sum_{j=1}^N |\Gamma_{ij}|}

Where \Gamma_{ij} is the correlation between channels i and j, and N is the number of array elements.

5.1.2 Synthetic Aperture Beamforming
For moving receivers or transmitters, synthetic aperture techniques improve resolution:

p_{SA}(x,y) = \sum_{n=1}^N p_n \left( t + \frac{\sqrt{(x-x_n)^2 + (y-y_n)^2}}{c} \right)

5.2 Multi-User Interference Management

5.2.1 Code-Division Multiple Access (CDMA)
Orthogonal coding separates multiple receivers:

s_i(t) = m(t) \cdot c_i(t)

Where m(t) is the modulation and c_i(t) is the orthogonal code for receiver i. The cross-correlation between codes satisfies:

\int_0^T c_i(t) c_j(t) dt = \begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } i = j \\
0 & \text{if } i \neq j
\end{cases}

5.2.2 Null Steering
Creating nulls at interference locations while maintaining gain at desired receivers:

\mathbf{w} = \frac{\mathbf{R}^{-1} \mathbf{a}(\theta_d)}{\mathbf{a}^H(\theta_d) \mathbf{R}^{-1} \mathbf{a}(\theta_d)}

Where:

· \mathbf{w} = Complex weight vector
· \mathbf{R} = Interference-plus-noise covariance matrix
· \mathbf{a}(\theta_d) = Steering vector toward desired direction

5.3 Environmental Adaptation

5.3.1 Temperature Compensation
Piezoelectric properties vary with temperature according to:

f_r(T) = f_{r0} \left[ 1 + \alpha_f (T - T_0) \right]

Where \alpha_f \approx -100 ppm/°C for PZT. Real-time temperature monitoring and frequency adjustment maintain resonance.

5.3.2 Humidity Compensation
Attenuation in air varies with relative humidity (RH):

\alpha_{air}(f, RH, T) = \frac{f^2}{c} \left[ \frac{1.84 \times 10^{-11}}{1 + (f/f_{rot})^2} + \frac{0.0128 \times e^{-2239/T}}{f_{vib}^2 + f^2} \right]

Where f_{rot} and f_{vib} are relaxation frequencies dependent on RH and temperature.

---

6. Safety Considerations & Regulatory Framework

6.1 Bioeffects & Exposure Limits

6.1.1 Thermal Mechanisms
The thermal index (TI) predicts temperature rise:

TI = \frac{W_{deg}}{W_{ref}}

Where W_{deg} is the derated power and W_{ref} is the power required to raise tissue temperature by 1°C. For diagnostic ultrasound, FDA limits TI < 6.0.

6.1.2 Mechanical Mechanisms
The mechanical index (MI) predicts cavitation risk:

MI = \frac{p_{r.3}}{\sqrt{f}}

Where p_{r.3} is the derated peak rarefactional pressure in MPa and f is frequency in MHz. FDA limits MI < 1.9 for diagnostic applications.

6.1.3 Audible Noise
Ultrasound can generate audible sounds through demodulation in the ear or through nonlinear interactions. Safe limits follow OSHA guidelines of <85 dBA for 8-hour exposure.

6.2 Safety Implementation

6.2.1 Multi-Layer Protection

1. Hardware Limits: Current and voltage monitoring with hardware shutdown
2. Software Limits: Real-time MI and TI calculation with power reduction
3. Physical Detection: PIR motion sensors and acoustic echo-location
4. User Controls: Emergency stop button and keylock operation

6.2.2 Fail-Safe Design

· Watchdog timers on all processors
· Redundant safety microcontrollers
· Graceful degradation rather than catastrophic failure
· Comprehensive logging of safety events

6.3 Regulatory Pathways

6.3.1 Medical Devices (FDA 510(k))

· Classification: Class II (special controls)
· Predicate devices: Ultrasound physical therapy equipment
· Required testing: Electrical safety, EMC, biocompatibility, performance

6.3.2 Industrial Equipment (UL/CE)

· Standards: UL 61010-1, IEC 61326
· Required testing: Electrical safety, EMC, environmental

6.3.3 Consumer Products

· Standards: FCC Part 15, IEC 62368-1
· Required testing: EMC, electrical safety, usability

